  "diary": "Woke early to water the rooftop garden—the basil's coming in thick this year, which made me smile. Had my coffee and spent a lazy morning with a vinyl catalog before heading out to Ballard. The farmers market was packed but unhurried; I grabbed fresh tomatoes and some gorgeous leafy greens from a vendor I've gotten to know over the years. We talked about heirloom varieties while the crowd flowed around us. Wandered through a couple record shops after, just browsing, no real mission. Back home by midday, and I made a simple lunch with the fresh stuff—tasted like the season itself. Spent the afternoon tending the garden, deadheading and organizing my notes. Made pasta for dinner with those herbs and tomatoes, put on some Coltrane. Sat with a book as the light faded. It's been a quiet Saturday, the kind that fills the tank.",
  "thought_process": "I needed this kind of day. Work's been intense lately—long shifts at the hospital drain something you don't always get back. Seeing the overcast weather and knowing the markets were open felt like permission to slow down. I skipped the Mariners game and the SoDo crowds without hesitation; that's not what I needed today. Instead, I built the day around things that ground me: the garden, the records, the farmers market ritual. The fresh ingredients weren't just groceries—they were a way of staying connected to seasons and rhythms outside the fluorescent ER. By afternoon, I could feel the tension from the week loosening. This was intentional quietness, not avoidance.",
  "end_state": {
    "location": [
